*****
[2] Cholera - Kenya (Nairobi County)
Date: Fri 8 May 2015
Source: The Star [edited]
http://www.the-star.co.ke/news/eight-dead-about-100-admitted-kibera-cholera-outbreak#sthash.jURwCYBb.dpbs


4 more people have died and nearly 100 hospitalized following the cholera outbreak in Kibera slum, Nairobi. 1 person found dead at Muthurwa market on Friday, 8 May 2015, had symptoms of acute diarrhoea and dehydration, St John Ambulance said. "Overpopulated areas with poor drainage and sanitation such as Mathare, Kibera, and Eastleigh are the most affected," Communications director Fred Majiwa said in a statement.

Majiwa said heavy rains and flash floods in Nairobi and its environs have promoted the spread of the disease. He urged patients to drink plenty of lightly salted water to replace lost fluids and seek treatment. "Cholera is highly treatable but can cause death quickly due to acute dehydration," he said.

4 others from Kibera died at Mbagathi District Hospital on Tue, 5 May 2015.

"Poor drainage and sewerage systems, dirty water and food are the main causes of this outbreak," said the hospital's CEO Andrew Suleh.

Suleh said some patients are sharing beds and that they may be forced to set up tents in the compound to accommodate the rising number. "We have only 4 wards here and each ward has 6 beds. This means we can only accommodate 24 patients at a time," he said.

Governor Evans Kidero said health workers were on high alert and asked residents to observe good standards of food hygiene.

[Byline: Nancy Agutu]

